{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}} {{Use British English|date=April 2016}} {{Infobox football biography | name= Ryan Kent | image = RyanKent.jpg | caption = Kent with Liverpool U21 at [[Goodison Park]] on 30 April 2015 | fullname = Ryan Kent<ref>{{cite web |title=Premier League clubs publish retained lists |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/408901 |publisher=Premier League |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1996|11|11}}<ref name="Premier League">{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/13509/Ryan-Kent/overview |title=Premier League Player Profile Ryan Kent |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2017 |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Oldham]], England | height = {{convert|1.72|m|order=flip}}<ref name="Premier League"/> | position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]<ref name="coventrytelegraph.net">{{cite web |last=McCartney |first=Aidan |url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/sport/football/football-news/who-ryan-kent-seven-things-10013378 |title=Who is Ryan Kent? Seven things you need to know about Coventry City's new signing |publisher=Coventry Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2016-01-09}}</ref> | currentclub = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] (on loan from [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]) | clubnumber = 14 | youthyears1 = 2003–2015 | youthclubs1 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] | years1 = 2015– | clubs1 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] | caps1 = 0| goals1 = 0 | years2 = 2015–2016 | clubs2 = → [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] (loan) | caps2 = 17| goals2 = 1 | years3 = 2016–2017 | clubs3= → [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] (loan) | caps3 = 44| goals3 = 3 | years4 = 2017–2018 | clubs4= → [[SC Freiburg]] (loan) | caps4 = 6 | goals4 = 0 | years5 = 2018 | clubs5= → [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] (loan) | caps5 = 10| goals5 = 0 | years6 = 2018– | clubs6= → [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] (loan) | caps6 = 17| goals6 = 5 | nationalyears1 = 2013–2014 | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]] | nationalcaps1 = 2 | nationalgoals1 = 2 | nationalyears2 = 2015–2016 | nationalteam2 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] | nationalcaps2 = 6 | nationalgoals2 = 1 | club-update = 19:28, 2 February 2019 (UTC) | nationalteam-update = }} '''Ryan Kent''' (born 11 November 1996) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder (association football)|winger]] for [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], on loan from [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].
A graduate of the Liverpool academy, Kent made his professional debut in 2015, before spending consecutive [[loan (sports)|loan]] spells with [[EFL League One|League One]] side [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] and [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]], winning the club's Young Player of the Season award with the latter. In 2017, he departed on loan once again, joining [[Bundesliga]] side Freiburg.
He is also a former England youth international, having previously represented his nation at [[England national under-18 football team|U18]] and [[England national under-20 football team|U20]] levels.
==Club career== ===Liverpool=== ====Early career==== [[File:RyanKent2.jpg|thumb|left|Ryan Kent after a friendly match Liverpool U18s at Kirkby Academy]] Oldham-born Kent joined Liverpool at the age of seven and progressed through the Liverpool academy to become a regular member of the U21 squad.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/team/academy/player/ryan-kent |title=Ryan Kent |publisher=Liverpool FC |date= |accessdate=2016-01-09 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229091220/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/team/academy/player/ryan-kent |archivedate=29 December 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> After an impressive end to the 2014–15 campaign for the reserves his performances were rewarded with a new 4 and 1/2 year contract in March 2015.<ref name="coventrytelegraph.net">{{cite web |last=McCartney |first=Aidan |url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/sport/football/football-news/who-ryan-kent-seven-things-10013378 |title=Who is Ryan Kent? Seven things you need to know about Coventry City's new signing |publisher=Coventry Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2016-01-09}}</ref> This was followed by a call-up to the first-team squad for their 2015 pre-season tour with the player being named in Liverpool's 30-man squad for their tour of [[Thailand]], Australia and [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Liverpool's 30-man tour squad confirmed |url=http://www.lfctour.com/news/latest-news/liverpool-s-30-man-tour-squad-confirmed |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=11 July 2015 |accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref> On 17 July 2015 Ryan Kent made his first-team debut when he came off the bench in the 2–1 win over Australian A-League side Brisbane Roar and was handed a first-team squad number for the Reds.
====Loan to Coventry City==== Liverpool received a number of offers to take Kent on loan after the player impressed in preseason.<ref>{{cite web |last=Pearce |first=James |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-fc-consider-loan-offers-9791888 |title=Liverpool FC consider loan offers from Championship clubs for Ryan Kent |publisher=Liverpool Echo |date=2015-08-04 |accessdate=2016-01-09}}</ref> Kent eventually joined [[Coventry City]] in September 2015 on a youth loan deal for four months until 16 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/signing-ryan-kent-coventry-city-liverpool-2679255.aspx |title=Coventry City snap up Liverpool midfielder Ryan Kent on a youth loan deal |publisher=CCFC Official Site |date=2015-09-10 |accessdate=2015-09-10}}</ref> Kent made his professional debut while on youth loan at [[Coventry City]] as a substitute on 12 September 2015 in a 1–0 [[Football League One|League One]] loss to [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/x-2683389.aspx |title=Scunthorpe United 1–0 Coventry City |publisher=CCFC Official Site |date=2015-09-12 |accessdate=2015-09-12}}</ref> On 3 November, Kent played and scored in a 4–3 win over Barnsley.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34644924 |title=Coventry 4–3 Barnsley |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=3 November 2015 |accessdate=29 August 2016}}</ref> The next day it was announced that he would return to Liverpool during the upcoming international break to be assessed by new Liverpool manager [[Jürgen Klopp]].<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.thisisanfield.com/2015/11/klopp-invites-ryan-kent-back-to-melwood-following-impressive-coventry-city-goal/ |title=Klopp invites Ryan Kent back to Melwood following impressive Coventry City goal |publisher=This Is Anfield |date= |accessdate=2016-01-09}}</ref>
On 5 January 2016 he was recalled by Liverpool and was named in the first-team to make his competitive debut for them, starting the [[FA Cup]] third round match away to [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]]. The match ended 2–2 with Kent being withdrawn from the action after 57 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/35155398 |title=Exeter City – Liverpool |date=8 January 2016 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref>
[[File:Ryan Kent.jpg|150px|thumb|Kent playing for [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in 2018]]
====Loan to Barnsley==== On 26 July 2016, Kent was loaned to [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] for the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ryan Kent makes loan move to Barnsley |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/229278-ryan-kent-makes-loan-move-to-barnsley |publisher=Liverpool FC |date=26 July 2016 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> He scored his first goal for them in a 4–0 win against [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] on 27 August 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37138603 |title=Barnsley 4–0 Rotherham |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=27 August 2016 |accessdate=29 August 2016}}</ref> Ryan Kent was named Barnsley's Young Player of the Season at the club's end of season awards.<ref>https://www.thisisanfield.com/2017/04/liverpool-loanee-ryan-kent-wins-barnsleys-young-player-season-award/</ref>
====Loan to SC Freiburg==== On 10 August 2017, after an impressive preseason, Kent signed a new long term contract with Liverpool,<ref>http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/271498-ryan-kent-signs-new-long-term-liverpool-deal</ref> and was loaned out to Freiburg for the season on the last day of the summer transfer window.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ryan Kent joins SC Freiburg on season-long loan |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/273896-ryan-kent-joins-sc-freiburg-on-season-long-loan |work=Liverpool FC |date=31 August 2017}}</ref>After making just six appearances, Kent's loan spell at Freiburg was terminated and he returned to parent club Liverpool on 8 January.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ryan Kent cleared to play after Reds return |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/286664-ryan-kent-cleared-to-play-after-reds-return |work=Liverpool FC |date=8 January 2018}}</ref>
====Loan to Bristol City==== On 12 January 2018, Ryan Kent joined Bristol City on loan until the end of the season.<ref>https://www.bcfc.co.uk/news/city-loan-in-liverpool-s-kent/</ref>
====Loan to Rangers ==== On 22 July 2018, Kent joined [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] on season-long loan for the 2018/19 season.<ref>{{ cite news | url=https://rangers.co.uk/news/headlines/rangers-sign-ryan-kent/ | title=Rangers Sign Ryan Kent | publisher=Rangers Football club | work=Rangers.co.uk | first=Nick | last=Thomson }}</ref>
==International career== On 27 August 2015, Kent was called up to the [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] squad for a double header against the Czech Republic.
